GSoC 2019 sgdnet Tests

Qincheng Lu qinchenglu@gmail.com, 3/15/2019

Easy Test

This part is a comparison between sgdnet, glmnet and ncvreg, in terms of the time and loss for gaussian, logistic and multinomial families. I use the loss function defintion as follows, where \(\lambda\) is the parameter for lasso penalty (for R code).

  • Gaussian: \(\frac{1}{2}\left \| \boldsymbol{XW} -\boldsymbol{y} \right \| ^{2} + \lambda \left \| \boldsymbol{W} \right \|_{1}\).

  • Logistic regression:
    • Loss = \(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n} \rho_{W}(\boldsymbol{X_{i}},{y{i}}) + \lambda \left \| \boldsymbol{W} \right \|_{1}\);
    • \(\rho_{W}(\boldsymbol{X},{y}) = -\boldsymbol{y}(\sum_{j=1}^{p+1} \boldsymbol{w}_{j}\boldsymbol{x}^{(j)}) + log(1+ exp(\sum_{j=1}^{p+1} \boldsymbol{w}_{j}\boldsymbol{x}^{(j)}))\).
  • Multinomial families:
    • Loss = \(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n} \rho_{W}(\boldsymbol{X_{i}},{y{i}}) + \alpha \sum_{k=1}^{c} \left \| \boldsymbol{W^{(k)}} \right \|_{1}\);
    • \(\rho_{W}(\boldsymbol{X},{y}) = -(\sum_{j=1}^{p+1} \sum_{k=1}^{c} \boldsymbol{y_{l}} \, \boldsymbol{w}^{(k)}_{j} \boldsymbol{x}^{(j)}) + log(1+ exp(\sum_{j=1}^{p+1}\sum_{k=1}^{c} \boldsymbol{w}^{(k)}_{j} \boldsymbol{x}^{(j)}))\), where \(\boldsymbol{y}_{l} = I(\boldsymbol{y}=l), l = 1,...,c\).

The test will use eyedata from flare package for Gaussian, covtype.binary and covtype from LIBSVM for logistic and multinomial regression. The performance evaluations are based on L1-regularized models. Here I follow the test method of GSoC 2018 SAGA project, change row and column by sampling a certain number of features and observations on datasets (My R code).

For Gaussian and Logistic, we shrink lambda = 1/(ncol). But for Multinomial, this way makes glmnet fails to converge sometimes. So we make lambda = 1/sqrt(ncol). And ncvreg has not implemented multinomial yet, then sdgnet is compared to glmnet only. For all models, standardization is enabled. We can see that, although sgdnet spends more time (ms) than glmnet and ncvreg when row and column grow.

In terms of loss, sgdnet beats glmnet for Multinomial, especially when ncol is large. For Gaussian, sgdnet is better than glmnet and ncvreg gives smallest loss. For Logistic, sgdnet beats ncvreg, and is similar with glmnet.

Median Test

This part use RcppEigen to write a class that defines the lasso (l1) penalty. The class has method prox to evaluate the proximal operator, and method loss to evaluate the loss \(\alpha \left \| \boldsymbol{W} \right \|_{1}\), where \(\lambda\) is the rate for gradient descent and \(\alpha\) is the lasso parameter.

Here is the methodology that I follow. In each iteration, we first conduct the gradient descent:\(\boldsymbol{W}^{\frac{t}{2}+1} = \boldsymbol{W}^{t} -\lambda \nabla f(\boldsymbol{W}^{t})\). Then we evaluate the proximal operator with respect to \(\lambda \times \alpha \, lasso\), by solving a minimization problem: \(\boldsymbol{W}^{t+1} =\underset{\boldsymbol{y}\in \mathbb{R}^{p+1}}{arg min} \{\frac{1}{2}\left \| \boldsymbol{y}- \boldsymbol{W}^{\frac{t}{2}+1} \right \| ^{2} + \lambda \times \alpha \, lasso\}\). When the penalty is lasso, the solution is soft-threshold. Then the updated \(\boldsymbol{W}^{t+1}\) has every element equals to \(\frac{w_{j}}{|w_{j}|} max\{ 0, |w_{j} -\alpha \lambda | \}\), \(j = 1,...,p+1\).

In l1.h(link), we define the class.

class l1{
public:
  l1(Eigen::MatrixXd W_, double alpha_, double rate_);
  Eigen::MatrixXd prox();
  double loss();
private:
  Eigen::MatrixXd W;
  double alpha;
  double rate;
};

And the corresponding functions prox() and loss() are defined in SGD.cpp(link).

l1::l1(Eigen::MatrixXd W_, double alpha_, double rate_): W(W_), alpha(alpha_), rate(rate_) {}
Eigen::MatrixXd l1::prox(){
  int n = W.rows();
  Eigen::MatrixXd Wnew = W;
  double w = 0;
  double tmp = 0.0;
  for (int i=0; i<n; i++){
    w = W(i,0)/std::abs(W(i,0));
    tmp = W(i,0) - alpha*rate;
    if (tmp < 0){Wnew(i,0)=0;}
    else {Wnew(i,0) = tmp*w;}
  }
  return(Wnew);
}

double l1::loss(){
  int n = W.rows();
  double loss = 0.0;
  for (int i=0; i<n; i++){loss+=std::abs(W(i,0));}
  loss = loss * alpha;
  return(loss);
}

We can do a test and compare it with the result from lm(), who uses QR decomposition.

library(sgdtest)
set.seed(0)
x <- runif(1000, -5, 5)
y <- x + rnorm(1000) + 3
X <- matrix(cbind(1, matrix(x)), nrow = 1000)
y <- matrix(y, nrow = 1000)
# use the fit from a simple ols
f1 <- lm(y ~ x)
W <- matrix(f1$coefficients, ncol=1)
W
##           [,1]
## [1,] 2.9579215
## [2,] 0.9848356
lasso <- new(l1, W, 0.01, 1)
lasso$prox() # proximal operator(soft thresholing)
##           [,1]
## [1,] 2.9479215
## [2,] 0.9748356
lasso$loss() # evaluate the loss
## [1] 0.03942757

## Hard Test

Rather than evaluating full gradient, stochastic gradient descent randomly chooses a number of observations (here I set to one) and updates the fit based on the gradient of these observations. The function is defined in SGD.cpp.

Eigen::MatrixXd SGD(const Eigen::MatrixXd & X, 
                     const Eigen::MatrixXd & y, 
                     const int & iter, 
                     const double & rate, 
                     const double & alpha)
{
  /**Intialization*/
  int n = y.size();
  int m = X.cols();
  int idx = 0;
  Eigen::MatrixXd error(1,1);
  Eigen::MatrixXd W(m,1);
  Eigen::MatrixXd Gradient(m,1);
  error.fill(0.0);
  W.fill(0.0);
  Gradient.fill(0.0);
  
  /**Iteration*/  
  for(int i=0; i<iter; i++){
    /**Generate random number*/
    Rcpp::IntegerVector pool = Rcpp::seq(0, n-1);
    std::random_shuffle(pool.begin(), pool.end());
    idx = pool[0];
    
    /**Gradient Descent*/
    error = X.row(idx)*W - y.row(idx);
    Gradient = X.row(idx).transpose()*error;
    W = W - Gradient * rate;
    
    /**lasso penality*/
    if (alpha != 0.0){
      l1 s = l1(W, alpha, rate);
      W = s.prox();
    }
    
  }
  return W;
}

By setting alpha to a nonzero value, the function uses the lasso penalty class from the previous test to regularize the model. Using the simple ols before, we can test this function.

w1 <- SGD(X,y, 1500, 0.01, 1) # with l1 penalty
w2 <- SGD(X,y, 1500, 0.01, 0) # without penalty
# present the result
result <- cbind(W, w1,w2)
rownames(result) <- c("intercept","x")
colnames(result) <- c("lm()","SGD with l1","SGD without l1")
print(result)
##                lm() SGD with l1 SGD without l1
## intercept 2.9579215   1.9403007       2.848306
## x         0.9848356   0.9210132       1.086994
